<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="569" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,394,635]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,466,491]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[330,490,467,491]" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Drilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bleusei">
<emphasis box="[330,490,467,491]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">Drilus bleusei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from its congeners occuring in the Aegean region (including 
<taxonomicName authority="Pic, 1914" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1914" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Drilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="attenuatus">
<emphasis box="[1283,1436,467,490]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">D. attenuatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Pic" box="[151,278,502,527]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" refString="Pic, M. (1914 b) Notes diverses, descriptions et diagnoses (Suite). L`Echange, Revue Linneenne, 30, 49 - 51." type="journal article" year="1914" yearSuffix="b">
Pic, 
<number box="[204,262,502,527]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="1914.0">1914</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, hitherto only 
<taxonomicName box="[452,524,502,526]" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Drilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[452,524,502,526]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">Drilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species known from Rhodes) by having the following unique combination of characters: robust general habitus, reddish to light brown body coloration with only apical part of elytra black (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,181,574,599]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
), pectinate antennae (
<figureCitation box="[424,506,574,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">
Fig. 
<number box="[476,506,575,599]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
), pronotum considerably constricted anteriorly, widest in the first 
<number box="[1242,1252,575,599]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[1264,1278,575,599]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="3.0">3</number>
(
<figureCitation box="[1293,1375,574,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">
Fig. 
<number box="[1345,1375,575,599]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
), and short, wide male genitalia (
<figureCitation box="[456,539,610,635]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">
Fig. 
<number box="[508,539,611,635]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
