<subSubSection lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="570" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1820,2025]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,365,1820,1845]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">Redescription</emphasis>
. Male. Body medium-sized, 
<number box="[697,732,1820,1845]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="2.6">2.6</number>
times longer than width at humeri, dorsally convex (
<figureCitation box="[1338,1423,1820,1845]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">
Fig. 
<number box="[1392,1423,1820,1845]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Body coloration reddish to light brown, only apical 
<number box="[731,745,1856,1881]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number box="[754,767,1856,1881]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="5.0">5</number>
of elytra black; body covered with yellow pubescence.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1437,1820,2025]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,151,1149]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="570" pageId="6" pageNumber="569">
Head including eyes slightly narrower than anterior margin of pronotum. Head punctured, with wide, shallow depression between antennal sockets, lateral margins above eyes elevated, covered with long, sparse, erected pubescence; clypeal margin widely concave. Eyes medium-sized, hemispherically prominent, their frontal distance 
<number box="[151,186,2000,2024]" pageId="6" pageNumber="569" value="2.4">2.4</number>
times eye diameter. Labrum sclerotized, transverse. Mandibles robust, long, considerably curved, shiny, incisor margin with conspicuous tooth in middle part (
<figureCitation box="[684,769,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Fig. 
<number box="[738,769,151,176]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="16.0">16</number>
</figureCitation>
). Maxillary palpi slender, apical palpomeres obliquely cut; labial palpi tiny, apical palpomeres of the same shape as maxillary ones. Antennae 
<number box="[1117,1141,188,213]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="11.0">11</number>
-segmented, reaching one third of elytral length, scapus robust, pedicel short, small, antennomere 
<number box="[977,991,224,248]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="3.0">3</number>
rectangular, about 
<number box="[1214,1228,224,248]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="2.0">2</number>
times longer than pedicel, antennomeres 
<number box="[411,467,260,284]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="7.0" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="4.0">4–10</number>
pectinate, subequal in length, lamellae flattened, apical antennomere simple, longest, about 
<number box="[220,234,296,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="2.0">2</number>
times longer than stem of penultimate antennomere (
<figureCitation box="[832,915,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Fig. 
<number box="[884,915,296,320]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Pronotum transverse, widest at 
<number box="[575,586,332,356]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[597,612,332,356]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="3.0">3</number>
, at hind angles 
<number box="[811,846,332,356]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="1.2">1.2</number>
times wider than anteriorly, and 
<number box="[1251,1286,332,357]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="1.6">1.6</number>
times wider posteriorly than length at midline. Anterior margin bisinuate, lateral margins constricted in anterior part, convex, posterior margin slightly convex, posterior angles almost rectangular (
<figureCitation box="[958,1044,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Fig. 
<number box="[1013,1044,404,428]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="17.0">17</number>
</figureCitation>
); surface of disc sparsely covered with shallow punctures, with sparse semierect setae, pubescence denser at margins. Scutellum flat, triangle-shaped. Prosternum transverse, with frontal margin slightly convex, prosternal process short, wide, slightly elevated in middle part. Mesoventrite v-shaped, with frontal margin widely emarginate. Metaventrite large, trapezoidal, shallowly punctured. Elytra subparallel-sided, 
<number box="[701,736,548,572]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="1.8">1.8</number>
times longer than width at humeri, tapered apically, with longitudinal keels running from humeri towards apex (
<figureCitation box="[772,856,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Fig. 
<number box="[825,856,583,608]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="15.0">15</number>
</figureCitation>
). Each elytron covered with semierect pubescence, sparse basally and dense at lateral and posterior margins. Abdomen slender, ventrites with shallow punctures, with sparse, long hairs, denser at margins; penultimate ventrite slightly concave apically. Legs slender, slightly compressed, with sparse, long, semierect setae, coxae long, robust, trochanters slender, obliquely attached to femora, five tarsomeres, tarsomere 
<number box="[547,561,728,752]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="4.0">4</number>
shortest, apical tarsomere long, claws simple, slender, slightly curved.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Male genitalia stout, with phallus strong, considerably curved, with hook subapically on dorsal side, parameres with inner apical parts membranous; phallobase robust, widely U-shaped (
<figureCitation box="[984,1067,799,824]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Fig. 
<number box="[1036,1067,800,824]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="21.0">21</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,836,861]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Measurements</emphasis>
. BL 
<quantity box="[431,520,836,861]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.6" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="8.6">8.6 mm</quantity>
, EL 6.0 mm, WHe 
<quantity box="[740,828,836,860]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="2.1">2.1 mm</quantity>
, WHum 
<quantity box="[929,1018,836,860]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="3.4">3.4 mm</quantity>
, PL 
<quantity box="[1070,1158,836,861]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
, PWA 
<quantity box="[1236,1324,836,860]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
, PWP 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="2.6">2.6 mm</quantity>
, Edist 
<quantity box="[273,361,872,896]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
, Ediam 
<quantity box="[453,542,871,896]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.6 mm</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="570" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,908,933]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Distribution</emphasis>
. 
<collectingCountry box="[362,446,908,932]" name="Greece" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Greece</collectingCountry>
: Rhodes. Only the 
<typeStatus box="[668,716,909,933]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">type</typeStatus>
specimen is known to authors, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Wittmer" box="[1131,1308,908,933]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" refString="Wittmer, W. (1935) Risultati scientifici delle cacce entomologiche di S. A. S. il Principe Alessandro della Torre e Tasso nelle Isole dell'Egeo, II. - Malacodermata. (3. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der palaearktischen Malacodermata). Bollettino del Laboratorio di Zoologia generale e agraria del R. Instituto superiore agrario in Portici, 28, 247 - 256." type="journal article" year="1935">
Wittmer (
<number box="[1241,1299,908,933]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="1935.0">1935</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
mentioned additional single specimen from Rhodes, Neocoria.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="570" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,980,1005]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Remarks</emphasis>
. 
<taxonomicName box="[322,490,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Drilidae" genus="Selasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bleusei">
<emphasis box="[322,490,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Selasia bleusei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is transferred to 
<taxonomicName box="[682,753,980,1004]" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Drilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[682,753,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Drilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
based on the presence of the V-shaped mesoventrite and the shape of lateral pronotal margins (
<figureCitation box="[562,703,1015,1040]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Figs 17, 19</figureCitation>
). This species has pectinate antennae (
<figureCitation box="[1169,1257,1015,1040]" captionStart="FIGURES 15 – 22" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1691,1714]" captionTargetBox="[155,1429,699,1658]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[151,1436,687,1670]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 15 – 22. Structures of Drilus bleusei (Olivier, 1913). 15, habitus; 16, mandible; 17, pronotum (setae removed); 18, antenna; 19, mesoventrite; 20, last abdominal segments; 21, aedeagus; 22, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype), aedeagus. Scale bars = 2.0 mm (Fig. 15), 1.0 mm (Fig. 17 – 18), 0.5 mm (Figs 16, 19 – 22)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242681/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Fig. 
<number box="[1226,1257,1016,1040]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="18.0">18</number>
</figureCitation>
). Although the pectinate antennae can be found in several 
<taxonomicName box="[633,714,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Drilidae" genus="Selasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[633,714,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Selasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in Africa (
<emphasis box="[925,959,1053,1076]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">e.g</emphasis>
., 
<bibRefCitation author="Wittmer" box="[980,1139,1052,1077]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" refString="Wittmer, W. (1989) Die Familie Drilidae (Coleoptera) in Sudafrika, sowie Beschreibung von neuen Arten aus dem sudlichen Afrika (30. Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Fauna Afrikas). Entomologica Basiliensia, 13, 187 - 205." type="journal article" year="1989">
Wittmer 
<number box="[1079,1139,1052,1076]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="1989.0">1989</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), they are more typical for the Mediterranean 
<taxonomicName box="[367,439,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Elateridae" genus="Drilus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[367,439,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Drilus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species (
<bibRefCitation author="Kundrata" box="[546,789,1087,1112]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" refString="Kundrata, R., Kobieluszova, L. &amp; Bocak, L. (2014) A review of Drilini (Coleoptera: Elateridae: Agrypninae) of the Northern Levant, with description of a new species from Syria and a key to Levantine species. Zootaxa, 3755, 457 - 469." type="journal article" year="2014">
Kundrata 
<emphasis box="[661,713,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">et al</emphasis>
. 
<number box="[729,789,1088,1112]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), whilst the vast majority of 
<taxonomicName box="[1124,1205,1088,1112]" class="Insecta" family="Drilidae" genus="Selasia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1124,1205,1088,1112]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">Selasia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. have flabellate antennae with long lamellae (
<figureCitation box="[481,597,1124,1149]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1 – 6" captionStart-1="FIGURES 7 – 14" captionStartId-0="3.[151,264,1907,1930]" captionStartId-1="5.[151,264,1820,1843]" captionTargetBox-0="[157,1431,453,1863]" captionTargetBox-1="[154,1432,681,1755]" captionTargetId-0="figure@3.[151,1436,447,1883]" captionTargetId-1="figure@5.[151,1436,671,1767]" captionTargetPageId-0="3" captionTargetPageId-1="5" captionText-0="FIGURES 1 – 6. Habitus images of Selasia species. 1, Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype); 2, S. atriventris Pic, 1914 a (holotype); 3, S. boruckae Kundrata, 2012 a (paratype); 4, S. homhilia Geisthardt, 2003 (holotype); 5, S. merkli Kundrata, 2012 a (holotype); 6, S. socotrana Kundrata, 2012 b (holotype). Scale bars = 2.0 mm." captionText-1="FIGURES 7 – 14. Habitus comparison of Selasia arabica Geisthardt, 2003 specimens from different governorates. Yemen, 7, Al Hudaydah; 8, Al Hudaydah; 9, Ma'rib; 10, Al Mahwit; 11, Sana'a; 12, Dhamar; 13, Abyan. Oman, 14, Dhofar. Scale bars = 2.0 mm." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/242679/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/242680/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="570">
Figs 
<number box="[537,597,1124,1148]" pageId="7" pageNumber="570" value="7.5" valueMax="14.0" valueMin="1.0">1–14</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
